Introduction¶

In this project we will analyze the data associated with the valuation of 10,000 collected films associated mainly with the ratings of the users and the income generated. Some columns, like 'cast', 'genres' and 'production_companies', contain multiple values separated by '|'

The questions that I am trying to explore are:

  1. What is the most frequent genres of movie in the 21st century?
  2. How is the comparison in revenue and votes average of those films that had the highest budget in the last 10 years?
  3. Which actors participated in more films in each of the genres?

Data Cleaning (NaN Values, Format, Duplicated values)¶

  1. Review duplicate rows
  2. Review null values
  3. Review the format of the columns
  4. Eliminate the columns that will not be useful in the analysis to be carried out

According to the data that contains the columns with null values, we make a decision

  • cast 76 rows : default value NAN='Other'
  • homepage 7929 rows : create a flag column (1= with homepage, 0=without homepage)
  • director 44 rows : default value NAN='Other'
  • genres 23 rows : default value NAN='Other'
  • production_companies 1030 rows : default value NAN='Other'
In [9]:
df["cast"].fillna("Other",inplace=True)
df["flg_homepage"]=df["homepage"].isna()
df["director"].fillna("Other",inplace=True)
df["genres"].fillna("Other",inplace=True)
df["production_companies"].fillna("Other",inplace=True)

#We create a function since there are several columns that have several values separated by |
def uniq_values(df):
    uniq_list = []  #create a blank list
    list_genres = df.apply(lambda x: x.split('|')).values 
    
    for i in list_genres:
        for j in i:
            #print(i,j)
            if j not in uniq_list:
                uniq_list.append(j) #we will add each column value to a list
    return uniq_list

for y in year: #review in each year
    year_df_q1 = df_q1[df_q1['year'] == y]
    genres_i1 = list(year_df_q1['genres'])  
    genres_f1 = [] 
    
    for genre in genres_i1: # for splitting every entry in y_df[genres] with separator as "|" 
        for i in genre.split("|"):
            genres_f1.append(i)

    count_genres_f1=dict()    
    for i in genres_f1:
        count_genres_f1[i]=count_genres_f1.get(i,0)+1 
    
    for genre in uniq_values(df_q1["genres"]): 
        if genre not in genres_f1:
            df_ays_genr[genre].append(0)
        else:
            df_ays_genr[genre].append(count_genres_f1[genre])

def label_point(x, y, val, ax):
    a = pd.concat({'x': x, 'y': y, 'val': val}, axis=1)
    for i, point in a.iterrows():
        ax.text(point['x']+.02, point['y'], str(point['val']))

#we create the function with the structure above
def actor_max_movies_genres (df,genres):
    df_q3=df[df.genres.str.contains(genres)]
    cast_i1 = list(df_q3['cast'])  
    cast_f1 = [] 

    for cast_v in cast_i1: # for splitting every entry in y_df[genres] with separator as "|" 
        for i in cast_v.split("|"):
            cast_f1.append(i)

    count_cast_f1=dict()    
    for i in cast_f1:
        count_cast_f1[i]=count_cast_f1.get(i,0)+1 

    df_cast=pd.DataFrame(count_cast_f1.values(),index=count_cast_f1.keys(),columns=["num_movies"])
    return (df_cast["num_movies"].idxmax(),df_cast.loc[df_cast["num_movies"].idxmax()][0])

#example
actor_max_movies_genres(df,"Action")

('Jean-Claude Van Damme', 39)

Research Question 1 The most frequent genres of movies in the 21st century are Drama, Comedy and Thriller. If we do the same analysis in the 20th century, the genres with the highest number of movies are the same categories, however in the 21st century 55.6% more movies have been made of those genres.

Research Question 2 In the last 10 years, the movie that has generated the highest income is Avatar, which was released in 2009. On the other hand, we see that the movie with the highest average vote is the Dark Tower, released in 2008. With this we see that movies can have many revenue, without great acceptance and can have great acceptance without generating a large amount of revenue. Additionally we see that 80% of these movies (8 out of 10) are of the Adventure genre, 60% are Fantasy or Action. If we compare the votes of these movies with the total we see that these movies have better acceptance (7.34 vs. 5.97). Also these companies are in the fourth quartile of income.

Research Question 3 We see that the genre Drama has 42 appearances by the same actor (Robert De Niro), on the other hand we have Samuel L. Jackson who is the actor with the most appearances in various genres (action, Crime, Mystery and Thiller), additionally we have Richard Gere with 15 appearances in Romance and Robin William with 14 appearances in Comedy. Being the 4 actors who have participated in more than 10 movies of the same genre.
